Here's the full migration analysis and rewritten code for .NET 8.

## Pattern Classification

| API | Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | Works in .NET 8, but **obsolete in .NET 9** (`SYSLIB0046`) |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | Not cancellation-aware |

## Race Condition (Pre-existing Bug)

Multiple `Enqueue` calls can fire before `RunLoop` wakes — but after `WaitOne` returns, `Reset()` clears the signal and only **one** item is dequeued. Remaining items are stranded until the next enqueue.

---

## Migrated Code (Cooperative Cancellation)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var reader = _channel.Reader;
        var token = _cts.Token;

        try
        {
            while (true)
            {
                // Blocks until an item arrives OR the token is cancelled.
                // WaitToReadAsync().AsTask().Wait(token) would also work,
                // but the synchronous spin-wait approach below avoids
                // allocating a Task on every iteration.
                while (!reader.TryRead(out var item))
                {
                    // This throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
                    token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(millisecondsTimeout: 100);
                    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
                }

                Handle(item);

                // Drain any remaining items before blocking again
                while (reader.TryRead(out var extra))
                    Handle(extra);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — exit the loop
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel closed.");
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();            // cooperative — wakes the loop
        _thread?.Join(5000);      // wait for graceful exit
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `Channel<string>` | Thread-safe producer-consumer built-in; no manual locking |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationToken` | Cooperative signal; wakes `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Throws `OperationCanceledException` at next checkpoint |
| Single `Dequeue` per signal | `TryRead` drain loop | Fixes the race where queued items were stranded |

## Common Pitfalls

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — the #1 reason this code won't run on .NET 6+.
2. **Forgetting `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`** — without it, `CancellationToken` is inert; the loop never exits.
3. **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaks timers/callbacks. Always `Dispose()`.
4. **Assuming cancellation is instant** — it only fires at the next checkpoint. The 100ms `WaitOne` timeout bounds worst-case shutdown latency.
5. **`Thread.Interrupt` silently breaks in .NET 9** — even if your immediate target is .NET 8, avoid it now to prevent a second migration.
